Kid's sometimes can be better than adults when they are dealing with emergencies. They are surprisingly and sometimes brutally honest. However, often times they may not know their address or phone number or information that could provide a location for first responders. Therefore it is important for the parents to coach their children on what to do in case of an emergency. Most important details for a child to know would be address and phone number. Second would be to not hang up the phone, they may set down the phone so the call can keep recording and the operator can report what they are hearing in the background but this can be dangerous to both the caller and the first responders if the situation escalates and we are unable to advise the caller or update with pertinent information. In addition, coaching the child to if they feel something isn't right and they call 911 that they aren't going to be in trouble (as long as they aren't misusing a 911 emergency line which happens all the time). Kid's often times can't be as descriptive as adults so on our end it's important to ask close ended questions so that they can give simple answers. And last, but not least if you don't know just say so. It's better than making something up or providing false or inaccurate information. It's okay to not know - most people aren't expecting their crisis making it easy to not remember or forget little details. The kids one is really tricky though because I've personally experienced a call from a child where he specifically said someone had a gun and hurt someone and once the cellular tower updated a close enough ping to an exact address I told him that officers were coming out there and he immediately regretted the call because he knew he was in trouble for lying. I had no choice but to treat it like anything other than someone with a gun at that address. I've also spoke with children who were more levelheaded and calm compared to their guardian counterparts which to me is a good sign and a scary one because they've probably been exposed to these incidents so often that it becomes normal behavior to them. The bad apples don't always last very long however bad habits can be overlooked or even missed. Some examples of bad operators would be being rude to the callers or unsympathetic, or maybe not prioritizing the call exactly right, some can't wait to pass the buck. However there is a lot of grey area with this job that makes a lot of the calls difficult to know what exactly to do with it, i.e whether or not it is a police matter, even if it isn't a police matter the police can still go, if they can, should they? Can other resources be offered? Some might underestimate the seriousness and generate a call with a lower priority than it should/could be. Almost anything can be justified as long as you make a solid argument for what you did. Really the "bad" apples and the traits most noticeable are internal like the dispatchers asking in a condescending manner why you put the call in the way you did or just general attitude towards others. But all in all the complacency is probably the worst and most noticeable trait. This job nationally has an extremely low retention rate so other agencies may keep incredibly bad employees simply because they have to due to federal regulations in regards to minimum staffing requirements at Public Safety Answering Points. On the other hand the people who excel may also be the same who possess bad traits or bad habits. There are so many different personalty types and backgrounds of people here it is hard to say what traits they have that can be correlated to success because everyone kind of has there own style on the phones. I purposely sit by people that when I hear them on a call and listen to some of the things they say to the callers it makes me laugh out loud. However, there are a lot of kind, caring and compassionate people that I work with. Some are strictly business that are cold to the touch and some are the kindest most caring people you could ask to be doing a job like this. For the most part people who are good at building rapport, taking shit, being an effective communicator and not afraid to ask questions or inquire details you normally wouldn't ask people. The people who aren't designated to their comfort zone I went to school for law enforcement to pursuit a career as a police officer which I still intend to do. A position has just opened up with one of our agencies I intend to apply for. I briefly redirected because initially I was offered this job LITERALLY the day after I graduated and I mean, c'mon how often does that happen? Nonetheless this has been great experience for me and a great segue into my desired career but honestly requirement wise - high school diploma, good background and to be able to type 60 wpm. Training consist of 4 week academy, followed by approximately 4 weeks of training with an experienced call taker taking calls with their assistance. Probation is two phases, 6 months is your first phase and you get your uniform, second is Data training which is what I am doing right now at my one year. With new technology and new policies always being implemented or changed there will always be mandatory training and refreshment courses or new training in general. Initially training is hard because you can't control the calls you get and some people are like magnets to suicides or domestics while others get boring administrative calls. It is most certainly a stressful job and we are provided with a licensed counselor if we take a traumatizing call or if we feel as if we need to speak with one and we are encouraged to use it. In fact we are encouraged to use all the resources we can that are provided. We are only human and you never know how your calls are going to effect you. Luckily for me I am capable of leaving work at work when I am relieved of my shifts but doesn't mean that it isn't stressful or that I don't have times of mental anguish. We all have bad days. On my breaks I used to skip lunch just to chain smoke, now that I am smoke free since Thanksgiving I stay inside and read instead - it honestly was a great stress reliever but my health is more important and when you really want a cigarette and can't have one it only stresses you out more. One thing I find to be helpful for recovery is that we work 3 days on and then have 3 days off and then the following week we work 4 days on and have 4 days off, giving me a lot of free time to pursuit all of my hobbies or to travel or to literally just do nothing if decide to do so. It isn't uncommon to find morbid curiosity or dark humor when your business is that of plight and let me tell you business is good. Among the coworkers we often support each other and form a bond unique to most other workplaces. Thank you for your interest in my profession, a particular sector that is often forgotten about or with little acknowledgement, we are the first people you come in contact with during an emergency. Mind you that I am trying my best to provide as much detail and information on my sporadic downtime while trying to make sense. If you need any clarity or further explanation or if you feel that I did not fully answer your questions it would be my pleasure to go into more depth and try again!

Thanks!! Yeah for the most part every one of my coworkers are professional and great at what they do. And yes, I #8217;ve been subpoenaed twice for court but never have gone as they usually settle before the court date. It #8217;s actually not bad if you get subpoenaed because regardless you get paid minimum of 4 hours overtime and most often you are only there for 30 minutes or so.
